Observation Details: The pair seem to be very interested in last year's Cooper's nest. One was sitting on the nest for a few minutes. Later one bird twice was collecting nest material and flying to that area (but I was too far to see it add it to the nest).  I witnessed the two birds mating but didn't manage a photo.  They were switching areas in the park and were active and sometimes calling. They mostly were around the old Cooper's nest or in trees near the water and bridge.  A third hawk was initially listed as Red-tailed...it was soaring extremely high over the park. But on reviewing a photo I took of it and zooming in a lot to see it better I realized it was actually an immature Red-shouldered.

Locality: Arroyo Valley Trail (Santa Rita Road to I-680)
Observation Details: One Red-shouldered picked up a rodent and landed on a pine tree. As soon as it landed, another Red-shouldered arrived and tried to steal the rodent from it. But, the rodent fell onto the ground. The second hawk immediately dove down to retrieve it. It took it some time to locate it in the grass. It then flew away with the rodent to a palm tree. The first bird called desperately. Notice the most interesting fact in the interaction. The hawk doesn’t try to pull on the rodent, if you look closely, the thieving hawk was holding one toe of the other hawk in its beak and pinching hard on it, probably on a nerve, to entice an automatic release reaction and open the foot. It worked. Another scene observed during the walk : a crow attacked a red-shouldered hawk and the hawk escaped flying away very fast.
Continuing in this area. It put on a very good show along the Queensway close to Pineneedle Row. Many pictures and videos taken.

I wonder if it was curious about me or just didn't care about me at all?

Observation Details: This young hawk is what drew me into the area that led me to discovering the Cattle Egret. This hawk seemed to be trying to catch a Wood Duck that was hidden in the weeds. Several times it "hovered" or swooped down to within 4 feet of the water line and I could hear the alarm calls from at least one Wood Duck. I did not see the Wood Duck and it did not fly out of the area making me think it was guarding some younger ducks or was an immature duck itself.

Smallish buteo perched on the side of the road. First noticed the extensive red barring in chest, very much like a Cooper's Hawk. No tell-tale white chest of the Red-tailed Hawk. This bird was sitting in tree on edge of road surveying for rodents presumably. Definitely rare, but not unheard of this time of year for the southern part of the state. Bird was patiently sitting in tree showing little signs of agitation as I took a few photos before letting it resume its hunt.

Saw this beauty perched low in a maple below the lower field.  We watched as it calmly flew softly to the ground and briefly scratched in the leaves, and just as we wondered if it had cached something (we saw one of our nesting RSHAs cache half a rabbit once) it picked up an obviously dead frog, then flew back up to the original perch and consumed it.  Cool.

Struggled a bit to ID this -- a juvenile Red-Shouldered Hawk was my best guess, give the lack of color and the tail stripes, but the iris appears dark, which I thought would not be the case? Observation Details: One Red-shouldered picked up a rodent and landed on a pine tree. As soon as it landed, another Red-shouldered arrived and tried to steal the rodent from it. But, the rodent fell onto the ground. The second hawk immediately dove down to retrieve it. It took it some time to locate it in the grass. It then flew away with the rodent to a palm tree. The first bird called desperately. Notice the most interesting fact in the interaction. The hawk doesn’t try to pull on the rodent, if you look closely, the thieving hawk was holding one toe of the other hawk in its beak and pinching hard on it, probably on a nerve, to entice an automatic release reaction and open the foot. It worked. Another scene observed during the walk : a crow attacked a red-shouldered hawk and the hawk escaped flying away very fast.

Observation Details: The pair seem to be very interested in last year's Cooper's nest. One was sitting on the nest for a few minutes. Later one bird twice was collecting nest material and flying to that area (but I was too far to see it add it to the nest).  I witnessed the two birds mating but didn't manage a photo.  They were switching areas in the park and were active and sometimes calling. They mostly were around the old Cooper's nest or in trees near the water and bridge.  A third hawk was initially listed as Red-tailed...it was soaring extremely high over the park. But on reviewing a photo I took of it and zooming in a lot to see it better I realized it was actually an immature Red-shouldered.

Observation Details: This young hawk is what drew me into the area that led me to discovering the Cattle Egret. This hawk seemed to be trying to catch a Wood Duck that was hidden in the weeds. Several times it "hovered" or swooped down to within 4 feet of the water line and I could hear the alarm calls from at least one Wood Duck. I did not see the Wood Duck and it did not fly out of the area making me think it was guarding some younger ducks or was an immature duck itself.

had thought at first that this bird was a Cooper's Hawk. I was not able to photograph ventral side of bird, but, upon review of dorsal side, and reviewing several field guides,  I believe this bird is a Red-shouldered Hawk; e.g. dark eye, black bill with yellow cere; upperparts are brown mottled with white; tail is black with thin white bands;  it appears that the secondary coverts do have 2-3 pale bars, which is a field mark for RSHA. Also, it appears that the upper wing coverts show some reddish-brown. Bird was perched on a low branch in the forest; Sibley notes that RSHA "hunts mainly from a perch within forests" - which is what this bird appeared to be doing.

I spotted this juvenile at 10:55 perched on a Joshua Tree near the T junction east of P9. I watched it for nearly hour, perched mostly with a few foraging flights. It was perched about 15 minutes in the large Willow tree at the junction (photos). It then flew past me within arm's length, perching on top of my Forester (photos). It was not shy, typical of many juvenile hawks. After about 10 minutes, it flew close by me again back to the willow. It was probably getting too hot on the roof of my car. I saw it again at P1 during our lunch break, perching on the No Thru Access sign for a couple minutes.

Observation Details: I spotted the RSHA while cruising for my first-of-year Rough-legged Hawk. The streaked bib and barred belly on a compact buteo captured my attention. The bird rotated its body and allowed me to see the black and white checkering in the flight feathers and the thick-banded tail. (see first two attached images). The RSHA was perched comfortably when a Cooper's Hawk (COHA) flew into the same line of cottonwood trees. The RSHA chased away the COHA. I observed the white crescents in the outer wings of the RSHA as it flew to push away the COHA. Three birders that I had just separated from prior to this encounter were able to come to the location and see the bird. The pin for this checklist is the actual spot from which I spotted the RSHA.

Barring in flight feathers visible. Reddish barred breast, small in size, reddish brown mottled back over entire back. Compact in stature overall.

Bob D'Antonio found and photographed this small orange breasted Buteo yesterday.  After an extensive search we were able to relocate it today thanks to a group of Magpies which were perched in the same tree.  Initially thinking it was a Broad-winged Hawk, Nick Peterson suggested Red-shouldered Hawk.  One of my photos shows orange underwing coverts and extensive barring on the primaries, supporting Red-sholdered Hawk.  See Photos  Taos Counties first Red-shouldered Hawk!

I spotted this juvenile at 10:55 perched on a Joshua Tree near the T junction east of P9. I watched it for nearly hour, perched mostly with a few foraging flights. It was perched about 15 minutes in the large Willow tree at the junction (photos). It then flew past me within arm's length, perching on top of my Forester (photos). It was not shy, typical of many juvenile hawks. After about 10 minutes, it flew close by me again back to the willow. It was probably getting too hot on the roof of my car. I saw it again at P1 during our lunch break, perching on the No Thru Access sign for a couple minutes.

Observation Details: One Red-shouldered picked up a rodent and landed on a pine tree. As soon as it landed, another Red-shouldered arrived and tried to steal the rodent from it. But, the rodent fell onto the ground. The second hawk immediately dove down to retrieve it. It took it some time to locate it in the grass. It then flew away with the rodent to a palm tree. The first bird called desperately. Notice the most interesting fact in the interaction. The hawk doesn’t try to pull on the rodent, if you look closely, the thieving hawk was holding one toe of the other hawk in its beak and pinching hard on it, probably on a nerve, to entice an automatic release reaction and open the foot. It worked. Another scene observed during the walk : a crow attacked a red-shouldered hawk and the hawk escaped flying away very fast.

Identifying as Red-Shouldered based on fluffy rust striped breast and red shoulders, similar to more clearly ID’ed bird seen 3/6/19 at Gardiner Library WVRT entrance. Thanks!

Spectacular sighting—first spotted in center of power lines over Farmer’s Trnpke adjacent to WVRT entrance, then flew casually to several trees feet away over WVRT. Tore apart and ate something that looked furry (mammal—mole/mouse/vole?) and seemed to be glad to pose for pictures. Attitude was nonchalant and finally rested after eating in tree facing WVRT parking lot at Gardiner Library in full view of the world. This was NOT a shy bird. Thanks for a magnificent show, friend!

Locality: Hilton Head beach area near Seahawk Ln
Observation Details: Two birds in adult plumage, one immature.  The three were interacting, and all spent time sitting at the nest.  However, the two adults were acting in concert, frequently perched side by side.  It was unclear to me what their relationship to the immature bird was.  Certainly, this immature bird could not be recently fledged from this nest?  I don't know the nesting calendar of raptors in SC, but this seems impossible in mid-February.  Besides which, I have walked past this spot for the past ten days without seeing any Red-shouldered Hawks.  Could this immature bird be from the brood of a year ago, and staying with the parents until the next nesting, which is about to occur?  Could this be a would-be interloper, unrelated?  If anyone has insight into this, I would be very interested!  dbemont@rochester.rr.com

Observation Details: Juvenile, hung around the yard for about an hour.

Young and flying around in an exploratory way.  Initially came to perch on a tree near water to the displeasure of the resident titmice, then caught a snake and flew down by the path.  Pecked a bit at the snake, but didn't seem inclined to eat it in the end.  We used a different trail to avoid disturbing it and it flew around some more.  Distinctive reddish coloration on tail and shoulder, a reddish wash on the breast too.  Legs looking "skinny" compared to a Red-tailed Hawk - I think that this is a juvenile Red-shouldered Hawk.  Took a lot of photos, post several to allow correct identification.

Observation Details: Red-shouldered Hawk(Buteo lineatus) County Road Alley Island overlook August 22 2016 MJGood   bird lacks the dark patagial bar at the base of the underwing along the leading edge. One photo shows a hint of the pale crescent in the primaries, and those lightly streaked underparts are good Red-shouldered too. The closest thing to this would be juvenile Broad-winged, but that wouldn't show the pale crescent in the primaries and would be more heavily marked below. Thanks to Lewis Bevier.

Medium-sized hawk with reddish head, orange-red barring on chest, brown mantle, and black tail with white bands.    I had been looking for the RLHA (alas, no luck today) and was on my way home when I noticed five crows arranged in two trees, clicking and rattling and making other weird crow sounds.  I figured something must've attracted their attention so I pulled over; this bird was in a tree close to the crows and adjacent to the Methodist church near Hwy 9.  It flew across the street onto a utility pole, posed for several photos, and then headed back north into the woods.  I was rather pleased with myself for having found it, but learned upon arriving home that Dan N. had already "discovered" it three hours earlier.

Observation Details: I noticed a large Red-Shouldered Hawk (sex unknown) in the Sycamore Tree in my backyard while sitting on my back porch. Later, the same hawk flew over and landed on a shepherd's hook that holds a hummingbird feeder in my yard. I observed that there were no hummingbirds at the feeder during the entire time I watched. The hawk seemed to be scanning the ground in my yard near the fence. Although I didn't personally witness any, I have seen mice in that area. My next-door neighbor has a large fruit tree, and because I have bird feeders, I suspect that there may be mice around. The hawk stayed perched on the shepherd's hook for about twenty minutes before flying away in a northern direction.

Observation Details: One juvenile was standing in nest when I arrived, second screaming nearby. One in nest flew out, quite adroitly, so it had obviously fledged previously and just returned to nest for a visit. While I had 2 vocal juvies in view in trees near nest tree, I could hear a third bird screaming upstream. Not sure if it was an adult or juvie (as juvie screams didn't sound, to my ear, noticeably different from calls I've heard adults give). Got recording of the 2 near nest tree: incomplete recording of first bird, complete recording of vocalization of second bird right over my head.

Observation Details: Red-shouldered Hawk sat in a tree in our yard for about 1.5 hours - sometimes going onto the grass and eating worms, once sitting on the birdfeeder. It would switch trees. After 10  minutes, birds and even squirrels returned to the yard while it was there. It never appeared to dive on a squirrel or a bird.

I had to leave at 9:45.
